 and diversion of management attention. \n*   **Intense Competition and Rapid Technological Change:** The AI industry is nascent, highly competitive, capital-intensive, and rapidly changing. The company faces risks that it may not be able to successfully execute its AI strategy, achieve meaningful commercial adoption, or compete effectively in a consolidating market.\n*   **Viability of Orbital AI Compute:** The company plans to launch orbital data centers, but the viability of orbital AI compute depends on the cost advantages of solar energy relative to terrestrial sources. Breakthroughs in terrestrial energy (such as advances in nuclear energy) could materially diminish the viability of orbital AI infrastructure. \n*   **Terrestrial Overcapacity:** A material slowdown in the growth of AI applications and compute demand could result in existing terrestrial data centers sufficiently meeting demand, thereby reducing the need for the company\'s orbital AI compute infrastructure.\n*   **Prioritization of Long-Term Growth over Near-Term Profitability:** The company may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of its AI investments (such as obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing its own GPUs, and building data centers) at any time. This could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as it prioritizes long-term growth over near-term financial performance.',
